 Angha Ice Factory, and many small scale industries are running here.\n\nNira is one the Key Market Place for farmers nearby. Nira has Grampanchayat with 17 elected members from people who look after the financial, cultural affairs of town. It has a Grampanchayat building where all the elected members work for betterment of town.\n\n==Transport==\nNira is linked by railway to [[Miraj]] and [[Kolhapur]]. Long-route trains do not stop there. Roads around Nira are city roads of good quality.\n\nBy road, it is well connected to Pune via Jejuri, the famous temple town, and saswad. On the other side, it is also connected to a famous pilgrimage place, Pandharpur via Phaltan. Third major town it connects is Baramati, the emerging industrial town.\n\nTo all these places, regular road transport (S. T.) buses are available. Takes around 2\u20132.5 hours from Pune, 1.5 hours from baramati. Some 2.5 hours from Pandharpur.\n\n==Temples==\nA very famous Temple of Datta on the bank of river Nira once visited by then Shree Sreedhar Swamy. Nira has many more temples, including one Saibaba  temple is thebiggest temple, located in ward no 4. Jyotirling Temple at Gulunche is very famous for Katebaras Yatra 5&nbsp;km from to Nira. Kate Baras Yatra is celebrated for 12 days, started from Dipawali Padwa. Before starting of yatra, on its first day, people do 'Ghatsthapana' (a special pooja to start yatra). During Kate Baras Yatra, people keeps fast for 12 days, daily Kirtan and Chhabina (Dhole and lazim is played during yatra)is arranged by villagers. on its 11th day i.e. on Kartik Shuddha Ekadashi, Palkhi moves for Nira Snan. On last day, Bhaktgan jumps in spines of babool tree. \n\nAlso there is a Panchayatan temple (temple of five lords) which is spacious and surrounded by beautiful garden. It is owned by the chemical factory Jubilant Life Sciences and is located on Nira\u2013Baramati road. There is also a Temple of Mahadev which is established by Lt. Damodarsheth Shankarsheth Garule in the memories of his beloved wife Sonubai in 1951 and it is located on the bank of Nira River. It is also a very holy place to visit, which is located in Shivtakrar around 2&nbsp;km from the railway station.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\nwww.niratech.com\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Pune district]]\n", "name_user": "SAGARBHOSALE44", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nira,_Maharashtra"}
{"title_page": "Alexandre Maspoli", "text_new": "{{short description|French sculptor and athletics competitor}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Expand French|Alexandre Maspoli|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name             = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = File:Alexandre Maspoli.jpg\n| image_size       = 200\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Maspoli in 1908\n<!-- Personal information -->\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1875|9|29|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Lyon]], France\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|1943|9|25|1875|9|29|df=y}}\n| death_place      = \n| height           = 170cm<ref name=SR/>\n| weight           = 91kg<ref name=SR/>\n| module           = \n<!-- Sport -->\n| country          = France\n| sport            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Olympic weightlifting|Weightlifting]]\n*[[Standing long jump]]\n*[[Sculpture]]}}\n| module2          = \n<!-- Achievements and titles -->\n| worlds           = 1902\n| nationals        = 1905\n| olympics         = [[1906 Intercalated Games|1906]]\n<!-- Medal record -->\n| show-medals      = y\n| medaltemplates   = {{MedalSport|[[Olympic weightlifting|Weightlifting]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{flag|FRA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[World Weightlifting Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|1902 London|Combined}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Intercalated Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[1906 Intercalated Games|1906 Athens]]|[[Weightlifting at the 1906 Intercalated Games|Two hand lift]]}}\n| module3          = \n}}\n\n'''Alexandre Maspoli''' (29 September 1875 - 25 September 1943)<ref name=SR>{{cite web| url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ma/alexandre-maspoli-1.html| title=Alexandre Maspoli| work=Sports Reference| accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> was a French sculptor and [[Olympic weightlifting|weightlifter]]. He came joint third in the two hand lift event at the [[1906 Intercalated Games]] in Athens.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Sports career===\nMaspoli was born in [[Lyon]], France.<ref name=GGI>{{cite web| url= http://gginews.in/charles-darwin-the-forgotten-indian-holocaust/| title= Charles Darwin & The Forgotten Indian Holocaust| publisher=Great Game India| date=6 July 2017| accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> He was an amateur weighlifting champion 19 years in a row.<ref name=GGI/> Maspoli won the combined events at the unofficial 1902 Weightlifting World Championships, setting a new world record in the process.<ref name=Olympic>{{cite web| url= https://www.olympicchannel.com/en/athletes/detail/alexandre-maspoli/| title= Alexandre Maspoli biography| publisher=Olympic Channel| accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=Orange>{{cite web| url=http://halterophilie.cpb.pagesperso-orange.fr/histohaltero.htm| title= HISTORIQUE SUR L\u2019HALTEROPHILIE| language=fr| last=Mallet| first=Edouard|publisher=[[Orange S.A.]]| accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> In 1905, Maspoli won the French National Championships. In the throwing event, he threw {{convert|130|kg|lb}}.<ref name=Orange/> At the [[1906 Intercalated Games]] in Athens, Maspoli came joint third in the two hand lift event. Maspoli, [[Heinrich Schneidereit]] and [[Heinrich Rondl]] all lifted {{convert|129.5|kg|lb}}.<ref name=Mallon>{{cite book| url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=wXYwCgAAQBAJ| title=The 1906 Olympic Games: Results for All Competitors in All Events, with Commentary| last=Mallon| first=Bill| publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]| date=2015}}</ref>{{rp|146}} He also participated in the one hand lift event, where he finished fourth,<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1906/WLT/mens-unlimited-one-hand.html| title= Weightlifting at the 1906 Athina Summer Games: Men's Unlimited, One Hand| publisher=Sports Reference| accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> and the [[standing long jump]] event, where he finished 18th.<ref name=Mallon/>{{rp|54}} In the same year, he featured in {{ill|La Culture physique|fr}}, as an example of \"perfect masculine physicality\".<ref name=GGI/><ref>{{cite thesis |type=PhD |last=Swaminathan|first=Medha |date=2019|title=The Missing Link: Tarzan in the Early-20th Century French Fantasy Landscape |publisher=[[Wesleyan University]] |page=75}}</ref> In 1907, Maspoli retained his French National Championship title.<ref name=Orange/>\n\n===Sculpture===\n[[File:Monument \u00e0 Frantz Reichel.jpg|thumb|left|Monument to [[Frantz Reichel]], sculpted by Maspoli.]]\nAfter the [[First World War]], Maspoli was commissioned to build [[war memorials]] in [[La C\u00f4te-Saint-Andr\u00e9]] and [[Arcachon]].<ref name=Olympic/> The Arcachon memorial promoted [[pacifism]] and the loss of families in the war.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.pierrelagrue-jo.com/alexandre-maspoli-1875-1943/| title= Alexandre MASPOLI (1875-1943)| publisher=Pierre Lagrue| accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> He submitted two works, ''Jet du boulet'' and ''Mask of [[Pheidippides|Philippides]]'', for the [[Art competitions at the 1924 Summer Olympics|mixed sculpture event]] at the [[1924 Summer Olympics]] in Paris. He was not awarded a medal.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1924/ART/mixed-sculpturing.html| title=Art Competitions at the 1924 Paris Summer Games: Mixed Sculpturing| publisher=Sports Reference| accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> In 1928, Maspoli created a bust memorial to historian {{ill|F\u00e9lix Desvernay|fr}}.<ref>{{cite news| url= https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k64504710/f8.item.r=F%C3%A9lix%20Desvernay| title= En France et Hors de France| language=fr| work=[[Les Nouvelles litt\u00e9raires]]| via=[[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]]| date=28 April 1928| page=8| accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> In 1933, Maspoli was commissioned to create a monument to sportsman and journalist [[Frantz Reichel]] in the [[16th arrondissement of Paris]]. The sculpture was finished the following year.<ref name=Olympic/><ref>{{cite web| url= https://e-monumen.net/patrimoine-monumental/monument-a-franz-reichel-paris-16e-arr/| title= Monument \u00e0 Franz Reichel \u2013 Paris, 16e arr.| language=fr| publisher=E-momumen.net|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> For this monument, he became the first winner of the {{ill|Grand Prix de la Presse Sportive|fr}} award in 1934. The award was created by the Syndicat National des Journalistes sportifs (National Union of Sports Journalists) for the best \"sporting act\" of the year.{{efn|Sculpture was included in the definition of sport}}<ref name=BNF>{{cite news| url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k64525516/f5.image.r=S%C3%A9ph%C3%A9riades?rk=386268;0| title=L'Athl\u00e9tisme : organe officiel de la F\u00e9d\u00e9ration fran\u00e7aise d'athl\u00e9tisme| language=fr| last=Fr\u00e9mont| first=Gaston| work=[[French Athletics Federation]]| via=[[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]]| page=3| date=May 1955| accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> In 1938, he built a statue to politician {{ill|Julien Barbero|fr}} in Lyon.<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.leprogres.fr/rhone/2012/12/09/la-statue-en-memoire-de-julien-barbero-est-de-retour| title= La statue en m\u00e9moire de Julien Barbero est de retour| language=fr| url-access=subscription| work=[[Le Progr\u00e8s]]| date=9 December 2012| accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ma/alexandre-maspoli-1.html Sports Reference]\n\n[[Category:1875 births]]\n[[Category:1943 deaths]]\n[[Category:Weightlifters at the 1906 Intercalated Games]]\n[[Category:French male weightlifters]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1906 Intercalated Games]]\n[[Category:French male long jumpers]]\n[[Category:20th-century French sculptors]]\n[[Category:Olympic competitors in art competitions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French sculptor and athletics competitor}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Expand French|Alexandre Maspoli|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name             = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = File:Alexandre Maspoli.jpg\n| image_size       = 200\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Maspoli in 1908\n<!-- Personal information -->\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1875|9|29|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Lyon]], France\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|1943|9|25|1875|9|29|df=y}}\n| death_place      = \n| height           = 170cm<ref name=SR/>\n| weight           = 91kg<ref name=SR/>\n| module           = \n<!-- Sport -->\n| country          = France\n| sport            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Olympic weightlifting|Weightlifting]]\n*[[Standing long jump]]\n*[[Sculpture]]}}\n| module2          = \n<!-- Achievements and titles -->\n| worlds           = 1902\n| nationals        = 1905\n| olympics         = [[1906 Intercalated Games|1906]]\n<!-- Medal record -->\n| show-medals      = y\n| medaltemplates   = {{MedalSport|[[Olympic weightlifting|Weightlifting]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{flag|FRA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[World Weightlifting Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|1902 London|Combined}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Intercalated Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[1906 Intercalated Games|1906 Athens]]|[[Weightlifting at the 1906 Intercalated Games|Two hand lift]]}}\n| module3          = \n}}\n\n'''Alexandre Maspoli''' (29 September 1875 - 25 September 1943)<ref name=SR>{{cite web| url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ma/alexandre-maspoli-1.html| title=Alexandre Maspoli| work=Sports Reference| accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> was a French sculptor and [[Olympic weightlifting|weightlifter]]. He came joint third in the two hand lift event at the [[1906 Intercalated Games]] in Athens.\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Monument \u00e0 Frantz Reichel.jpg|thumb|right|Monument to [[Frantz Reichel]], sculpted by Maspoli.]]\n\n===Sports career===\nMaspoli was born in [[Lyon]], France.<ref name=GGI>{{cite web| url= http://gginews.in/charles-darwin-the-forgotten-indian-holocaust/| title= Charles Darwin & The Forgotten Indian Holocaust| publisher=Great Game India| date=6 July 2017| accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> He was an amateur weighlifting champion 19 years in a row.<ref name=GGI/> Maspoli won the combined events at the unofficial 1902 Weightlifting World Championships, setting a new world record in the process.<ref name=Olympic>{{cite web| url= https://www.olympicchannel.com/en/athletes/detail/alexandre-maspoli/| title= Alexandre Maspoli biography| publisher=Olympic Channel| accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=Orange>{{cite web| url=http://halterophilie.cpb.pagesperso-orange.fr/histohaltero.htm| title= HISTORIQUE SUR L\u2019HALTEROPHILIE| language=fr| last=Mallet| first=Edouard|publisher=[[Orange S.A.]]| accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> In 1905, Maspoli won the French National Championships. In the throwing event, he threw {{convert|130|kg|lb}}.<ref name=Orange/> At the [[1906 Intercalated Games]] in Athens, Maspoli came joint third in the two hand lift event. Maspoli, [[Heinrich Schneidereit]] and [[Heinrich Rondl]] all lifted {{convert|129.5|kg|lb}}.<ref name=Mallon>{{cite book| url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=wXYwCgAAQBAJ| title=The 1906 Olympic Games: Results for All Competitors in All Events, with Commentary| last=Mallon| first=Bill| publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]| date=2015}}</ref>{{rp|146}} He also participated in the one hand lift event, where he finished fourth,<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1906/WLT/mens-unlimited-one-hand.html| title= Weightlifting at the 1906 Athina Summer Games: Men's Unlimited, One Hand| publisher=Sports Reference| accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> and the [[standing long jump]] event, where he finished 18th.<ref name=Mallon/>{{rp|54}} In the same year, he featured in {{ill|La Culture physique|fr}}, as an example of \"perfect masculine physicality\".<ref name=GGI/><ref>{{cite thesis |type=PhD |last=Swaminathan|first=Medha |date=2019|title=The Missing Link: Tarzan in the Early-20th Century French Fantasy Landscape |publisher=[[Wesleyan University]] |page=75}}</ref> In 1907, Maspoli retained his French National Championship title.<ref name=Orange/>\n\n===Sculpture===\nAfter the [[First World War]], Maspoli was commissioned to build [[war memorials]] in [[La C\u00f4te-Saint-Andr\u00e9]] and [[Arcachon]].<ref name=Olympic/> The Arcachon memorial promoted [[pacifism]] and the loss of families in the war.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.pierrelagrue-jo.com/alexandre-maspoli-1875-1943/| title= Alexandre MASPOLI (1875-1943)| publisher=Pierre Lagrue| accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> He submitted two works, ''Jet du boulet'' and ''Mask of [[Pheidippides|Philippides]]'', for the [[Art competitions at the 1924 Summer Olympics|mixed sculpture event]] at the [[1924 Summer Olympics]] in Paris. He was not awarded a medal.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1924/ART/mixed-sculpturing.html| title=Art Competitions at the 1924 Paris Summer Games: Mixed Sculpturing| publisher=Sports Reference| accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> In 1928, Maspoli created a bust memorial to historian {{ill|F\u00e9lix Desvernay|fr}}.<ref>{{cite news| url= https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k64504710/f8.item.r=F%C3%A9lix%20Desvernay| title= En France et Hors de France| language=fr| work=[[Les Nouvelles litt\u00e9raires]]| via=[[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]]| date=28 April 1928| page=8| accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> In 1933, Maspoli was commissioned to create a monument to sportsman and journalist [[Frantz Reichel]] in the [[16th arrondissement of Paris]]. The sculpture was finished the following year.<ref name=Olympic/><ref>{{cite web| url= https://e-monumen.net/patrimoine-monumental/monument-a-franz-reichel-paris-16e-arr/| title= Monument \u00e0 Franz Reichel \u2013 Paris, 16e arr.| language=fr| publisher=E-momumen.net|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> For this monument, he became the first winner of the {{ill|Grand Prix de la Presse Sportive|fr}} award in 1934. The award was created by the Syndicat National des Journalistes sportifs (National Union of Sports Journalists) for the best \"sporting act\" of the year.{{efn|Sculpture was included in the definition of sport}}<ref name=BNF>{{cite news| url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k64525516/f5.image.r=S%C3%A9ph%C3%A9riades?rk=386268;0| title=L'Athl\u00e9tisme : organe officiel de la F\u00e9d\u00e9ration fran\u00e7aise d'athl\u00e9tisme| language=fr| last=Fr\u00e9mont| first=Gaston| work=[[French Athletics Federation]]| via=[[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]]| page=3| date=May 1955| accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> In 1938, he built a statue to politician {{ill|Julien Barbero|fr}} in Lyon.<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.leprogres.fr/rhone/2012/12/09/la-statue-en-memoire-de-julien-barbero-est-de-retour| title= La statue en m\u00e9moire de Julien Barbero est de retour| language=fr| url-access=subscription| work=[[Le Progr\u00e8s]]| date=9 December 2012| accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ma/alexandre-maspoli-1.html Sports Reference]\n\n[[Category:1875 births]]\n[[Category:1943 deaths]]\n[[Category:Weightlifters at the 1906 Intercalated Games]]\n[[Category:French male weightlifters]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1906 Intercalated Games]]\n[[Category:French male long jumpers]]\n[[Category:20th-century French sculptors]]\n[[Category:Olympic competitors in art competitions]]\n", "name_user": "Joseph2302", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:move image", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexandre_Maspoli"}
